A: The problem is that you're calling dataSnapshot.getChildren().iterator().next() in your loop, which means you're only ever getting the first child of each DataSnapshot.
Instead, you should be calling it.next() in your loop, which will give you each child in turn.
Here's how you can do it:
Iterator<DataSnapshot> it = dataSnapshot.getChildren().iterator();
while(it.hasNext()) {
    DataSnapshot ds = it.next();
    names.add(ds.getValue(String.class));
}

This will give you a list of all the children's values.

A: You are using the same iterator in each loop iteration. You should create a new iterator for each DataSnapshot.
Here is the corrected code:
for (DataSnapshot dataSnapshot1:dataSnapshot.getChildren()) {
    Iterator<DataSnapshot> it = dataSnapshot1.getChildren().iterator();
    while(it.hasNext()) {
        names.add(it.next().getValue(String.class));
    }
}

This way, you create a new iterator for each DataSnapshot in dataSnapshot.getChildren(), and you add all values from each iterator to the names list.

